FeedPackage.Description:
checksum - Command line file checksum validator.
checksum checks a file and returns a checksum for both md5 and sha1. To use checksum you would simply provide a file path and it will return the sum for the file.
Example: checksum -f="relative\path" Example: checksum -f="c:\absolute\path" -t=sha1
You can also check against an existing signature. To validate against an existing signature (hash) you would simply provide the file and the expected signature. When checking a signature, if the signature is valid it exits with 0, otherwise it exits with a non-zero exit code.
Example: checksum -f="c:\\path\to\somefile.exe" -c="thehash"
OPTIONS -?, --help, -h Prints out the options. -f, --file=VALUE REQUIRED: file - The is the name of the file. The file should exist -t, --type, --hashtype=VALUE Optional: hashtype - 'md5' or 'sha1' Defaults to 'md5'. -c, --check=VALUE Optional: check - the signature you want to check. Not case sensitive.

checksum - Command line file checksum validator.
checksum checks a file and returns a checksum for both md5 and sha1. To use checksum you would simply provide a file path and it will return the sum for the file.
Example: checksum -f="relative\path" Example: checksum "relative\path" Example: checksum -f="c:\absolute\path" -t=sha1
You can also check against an existing signature. To validate against an existing signature (hash) you would simply provide the file and the expected signature. When checking a signature, if the signature is valid it exits with 0, otherwise it exits with a non-zero exit code.
Example: checksum "c:\\path\to\somefile.exe" -c="thehash" Example: checksum -f="c:\\path\to\somefile.exe" -c="thehash" -t=sha1
SYNOPSIS
checksum [-t=sha1|md5] [-c=signature] [-f=]filepath
OPTIONS
-?, --help, -h Prints out the options. -f, --file=VALUE REQUIRED: file - The is the name of the file. The file should exist -t, --type, --hashtype=VALUE Optional: hashtype - 'md5' or 'sha1' Defaults to 'md5'. -c, --check=VALUE Optional: check - the signature you want to check. Not case sensitive.

FeedPackage.Description:
ChemBytes Draw is a compact .NET component allowing developers to integrate advanced chemical drawing and chemical information processing into any .NET project (WPF or Windows Forms).
This is a 30 day evaluation version, which later can be unlocked. No registration required.
As part of a .NET application, ChemBytes Draw on demand displays a fully featured chemical drawing editor, which also supports organometallic, polymer and peptide drawing. Content can be imported from other third party chemical drawing tools, e.g. ISIS/Symyx/Accelrys Draw, ChemDraw, Marvin, etc., via MDL clipboard content or via MDL format export files, including V3000 format. When the user closes the editor, the API takes over and exposes the chemical information for use by your own application. Thus, the molecular weights and elemental formulas of all entered reactants and products, their InChIKeys, bitmap and vector images, bounding boxes, the MDL reaction and molfiles, and the internal file format for database storage, etc. are available for further processing. ChemBytes Draw is written in 100% managed code, i.e. it is no wrapper around an existing Java or C++ functionality.
A sample Visual Studio project and sample files are available from the project site.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes: This is the first standalone release of ChemBytes Draw, which so far has been successfully field proven as part of our Espresso ELN software since 2 years now.

When the user closes the editor, the API takes over and exposes the graphical and chemical reaction, reactant(s) and product(s) information for use by your own application.
